<HEADLINE>
FT  04 DEC 92 / British Coal proposes measures to save 13 pits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH COAL urged the government yesterday to adopt plans aimed at saving
13 threatened pits and 8,000 jobs and to change the law to enable it to
adapt working patterns and significantly increase pit efficiency.
The proposals were attacked by unions, which said saving fewer than half of
the 31 pits earmarked for closure was not enough, especially as British Coal
envisages that seven of the 'saved' pits and 6,000 of the saved jobs would
go within five years anyway.
The National Union of Mineworkers and Nacods pit deputies union also oppose
law changes by which British Coal could introduce 24-hour working, seven
days a week. Mr Arthur Scargill, NUM president, said in Sheffield yesterday:
'This latest statement by British Coal displays further incompetence and a
refusal to accept the overwhelming evidence in support of keeping all 51
pits open.'
Separately, Mr Neil Clarke, British Coal chairman, said it was unlikely that
contracts with electricity generators would be signed before the government
published its energy review scheduled for the end of next month. He called
for longer contracts with the power generators than the five years at
present envisaged.
In its evidence to the Department of Trade and Industry's energy review,
British Coal proposed a series of measures that would, it said, enable it to
sell an extra 15m tonnes of coal a year over the next five years to the
England and Wales electricity generators and another 5m to industrial and
domestic customers, taking the total to 64m tonnes in 1997-98.
Mr Clarke said if British Coal were to be profitable, extra sales to
generators would have to be at the same price as agreed for lower volumes in
existing tentative deals. British Coal's proposals include:
Deferring the commissioning of Sizewell B nuclear power station for a number
of years, saving 3m tonnes of coal by 1997-98, and phasing out most Magnox
nuclear stations over the next five years, saving 5m tonnes.
Reducing gas burning at committed combined-cycle gas turbine plants and
refusing permission for others to be constructed, saving 6m tonnes.
Extending the UK tax on electricity - the fossil fuel levy - to electricity
imported from France and eliminating the present net inflow into Britain,
saving 6m tonnes.
British Coal wants a slower reduction in coal stocks than is now envisaged
and limits on the burning of bitumen-based orimulsion. It also backs the
deferral of plans for the proposed liberalisation of the electricity market
due for implementation in 1994 and 1998.
British Coal warned that without policy changes there would be only 11,000
deep-pit miners and 15 pits by 1997. Even with the changes there would be 25
pits compared with the present 50 and 17,000 miners.
None of those calculations incorporates the effects of the the proposed law
changes on alterations to working practices. British Coal says the changes
may cut average deep-mine operating costs of Pounds 1.27 a gigajoule by a
further 15p.
British Coal wants the government to repeal the 1908 Coal Mines Regulation
Act, which limits underground shifts to 7 1/2 hours. Because of travelling
time, many miners work only five hours at the coal face. British Coal wants
to increase that to eight hours, and for some miners that would mean 10-hour
shifts.
The corporation also wants the government to repeal of Section 46 of the
1946 Coal Industry Nationalisation Act, which establishes machinery for
consultation and conciliation and the modernisation of mines and quarries
legislation to allow more efficient management and supervision. It wants to
be able to make compulsory redundancies.
The Trades Union Congress has called on the European Commission to take
legal action to halt the pit closure programme.
</TEXT>
