<HEADLINE>
FT  04 DEC 92 / Land Rover set to win Pounds 150m order
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A Pounds 150M MINISTRY of Defence order for 6,500 light military vehicles
looks almost certain to go to Land Rover, the four-wheel-drive vehicle
subsidiary of British Aerospace-owned Rover Group.
Land Rover, based in Solihull, West Midlands, is the only company to have
been asked to build trial vehicles for the order out of 20 European and
North American manufacturers invited to tender in June.
The MoD normally selects three or four rival candidates to build evaluation
models for trials, typically lasting about 18 months. Land Rover will build
13 trial vehicles, based on its Defender 90 and 110 models.
If they are satisfactory, the company would expect to be given the volume
order, which is mainly for the Army. The MoD is Land Rover's biggest single
customer and the order is potentially the company's biggest single contract
for a decade. Delivery is scheduled over five years, starting in 1994.
Land Rover will also build some larger Defender trial vehicles for another
MoD contract for 200 four-wheel-drive utility trucks, in competition with
Steyr-Daimler-Puch of Austria. This year Land Rover expects to produce about
55,000 vehicles, 5,000 down on 1991. About two fifths of the total will be
its Discovery leisure vehicles, with the balance shared equally between the
Defender and up-market Range Rover models.
The Solihull plant is working overtime and on Saturdays to maintain its
output level and to cater for higher demand. Like Jaguar, Land Rover has
found robust demand starting to reappear in North America.
Land Rover's October sales in the US, at 521, were more than double levels
of a year ago and are the second-highest in its history.
The company said yesterday it expected last month's sales to set a new
record at more than 600.
Demand for Jaguars in North America has picked up only during the past month
and has yet to be quantified by the company. In October, its US sales were
down on the same month of 1991 - at 614 compared with 926 - but the company
is sufficiently encouraged to have resumed five-day working.
</TEXT>
