<HEADLINE>
FT  04 DEC 92 / Accountancy pay 'up 2%'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ACCOUNTANTS' salaries rose by just 2 per cent in the past year, highlighting
the continued effects of the recession, Accountancy Personnel, the
recruitment firm, reported yesterday.
Demand for insolvency staff is beginning to level off in the north-east and
Scotland, suggesting that the worst of the downturn may be over in those
regions.
Wages for newly qualified accountants in industry and commerce fell by 3.5
per cent to Pounds 19,208, while those for qualified staff remained
unchanged at Pounds 23,222.
Salaries for students entering training contracts in accountancy firms rose
by 1.5 per cent to an average of Pounds 7,941. Wages for unqualified audit
staff in public practice were unchanged at Pounds 8,389, while those for
accounting technicians increased 2 per cent to Pounds 6,736.
Newly qualified chartered and certified accountants' salaries rose 2 per
cent to Pounds 19,041, while those with post-qualifying experience were up
3.5 per cent to Pounds 20,667.
Salaries for part-qualified accountants in industry and commerce jumped 4.5
per cent to Pounds 10,500, while certified and management accountant
trainees' salaries were level at Pounds 7,472.
Accountancy Personnel said technical skills, including using spreadsheets,
were a pre-requisite for job-hunters.
</TEXT>
