<HEADLINE>
FT  04 DEC 92 / Lloyd's staff levels to drop
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MORE THAN 200 jobs are to go at the Lloyd's Corporation, the body that
co-ordinates and regulates activities at the Lloyd's insurance market.
The cuts, announced yesterday by Mr Peter Middleton, Lloyd's chief
executive, are part of plans to reduce the organisation's budget by 18.4 per
cent to Pounds 117.9m in 1993 compared with Pounds 144.5m in 1992. Staffing
levels will fall from 2,200 to 1,990 over the next 12 months.
Mr David Rowland, chairman-elect, said: 'There is no possibility of the
market prospering without a substantial attack on costs.' A radical review
of the corporation's activities is under way and further cuts are not ruled
out.
Lloyd's also announced that Mr John Gaynor, 57, head of finance at the
corporation, is to take early retirement, while the contract of Mr Brian
Nicholson, a senior public-relations executive, will not be renewed.
The moves are part of a reorganisation of the corporation's management
structure.
Lloyd's is freezing pay levels of corporation employees, abolishing
flexitime arrangements and consolidating some benefits into basic pay.
The spending cuts will allow Lloyd's to reduce the expenses of Names, the
individuals whose capital supports underwriting at the market, and
syndicates, which in turn should make a return to profitability more likely.
The cost of membership subscriptions that Names must pay will be reduced
from 0.5 per cent of gross allocated capacity (the amount of premium income
a Name is allowed to accept) in 1992 to 0.4 per cent in 1993.
Rents paid by syndicates for space in the underwriting room are being
reduced from Pounds 307 a sq ft to Pounds 280 a sq ft.
Lloyd's also announced that its council, or governing body, had nominated Mr
Robert Hiscox, chairman of Roberts &amp; Hiscox, a managing agency, and Mr
Stephen Merrett, a leading underwriter, to be deputy chairman to Mr Rowland.
</TEXT>
