<HEADLINE>
FT  04 DEC 92 / 1,300 jobs to be shed at Royal Ordnance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WHITE, Defence Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ROYAL ORDNANCE, the armaments subsidiary of British Aerospace, yesterday
announced 1,300 job losses, the largest reduction since the company was
privatised in 1987.
The cuts, reflecting the general downturn in the defence business, affect 13
sites in England, Scotland and Wales and include management staff. Royal
Ordnance said it had to reduce its cost base to compete in the UK and
overseas.
An interim arrangement that guaranteed the company 80 per cent of certain
categories of ammunition purchases by the Ministry of Defence will end next
April. The company said it would be unable to sustain its present Pounds
550m annual turnover unless it increased its exports, now about 40 per cent
of its total business.
The latest cuts will reduce Royal Ordnance's workforce to about 6,100
against more than 15,000 when BAe bought the company from the government 5
1/2 years ago for Pounds 190m.
In the interim, the company has boosted its gun and ammunition businesses by
buying Sterling Armament and BMARC in the UK and Heckler &amp; Koch in Germany,
together employing more than 1,000.
Mr Jack Dromey, national secretary of the Transport and General Workers'
Union, said the cuts were 'a bitter pill we will not swallow'.
He claimed that union pressure had stopped the company from closing several
sites.
Royal Ordnance employees lobbied parliament on Wednesday amid union
predictions that up to 2,500 jobs might go, with the closure of three or
four plants. The company denied that it ever had such plans and hoped there
would not be further cuts. It said it planned to spend Pounds 40m next year
on capital investment and product development.
The US is to close four more military sites in the UK with the loss of at
least 81 civilian jobs. The bases are the US Marine Corps barracks in St
John's Wood, London; an airbase headquarters in High Wycombe, Bucks; and
contingency hospitals at Little Rissington, Glos, and Bicester, Oxon.
</TEXT>
