<HEADLINE>
FT  04 DEC 92 / Lender falls out with the modern generation: Bristol &amp;
West's proposal to back the nuclear family for mortgages
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Tony FitzSimons is worried about British society. 'There is a generation
that does not have the thrift mentality and does not fear losing their
homes,' he says. Unlike others who shake their heads at the ways of young
people, Mr FitzSimons is prompted by financial rather than moral concern.
Bristol &amp; West, the building society of which he is chief executive, has
fallen out badly with this generation in the past two years. After competing
with other lenders to sell mortgages in the overheated south-east housing
market of the late 1980s, it has paid the cost in the 1990s.
The society has suffered a wave of mortgage arrears and house repossessions
among its 190,000 borrowers. About 2.9 per cent of them were more than 12
months in arrears last year, the worst record of the top 25 societies. Its
half-year provision for bad debt quadrupled to Pounds 29.7m.
That is the reason why Mr FitzSimons is considering the bold step of pricing
mortgages by its assessment of the credit risk of borrowers. The policy will
mean that younger people, unmarried couples and, above all, young adults who
take out mortgages together will be charged more.
Mr FitzSimons says the move may be forced on Bristol &amp; West by its
experience of the past five years. The over-eager borrowers who were
encouraged by over-eager lenders in the 1980s have proved such a bad risk
that he believes it must discriminate in the future.
The underlying issue is that southern building societies lent in the 1980s
on the assumption that risk was largely covered by the boom in house prices.
Any repossessions would be covered by selling the property for a higher
price.
'We have not really examined people's ability to pay a debt over 25 years,'
Mr Fitz-Simons says. 'The fundamental tenet now should be that, rather than
the security value of the property.' Until now, societies have used only
people's income and the amount saved as a deposit as indicators.
That would change under Mr FitzSimons' proposal. Prospective borrowers would
be scored on various factors - most importantly age, marital status and
whether they have children - and the mortgage priced accordingly.
In spite of its unsettling implications, that was greeted with murmurs of
approval among societies yesterday. Mr Tim Melville-Ross, chief executive of
Nationwide Building Society, said: 'Some growth in segmentation is
inevitable. We have to make more judgments about our borrowers.'
Mortgage rates have already started diverging to reflect risk.
In consequence, many young first-time buyers are being priced out of the
market. No society will now lend more than 95 per cent of the property
price, and higher rates of mortgage guarantee insurance in effect lower that
to about 93 per cent.
Bristol &amp; West's move raises the possibility that the mortgage market will
now become segmented according to family status. Yet there are sizeable
obstacles.
The first is social acceptability. Probably the most controversial aspect of
the proposal is its implication for the way people live. As Mr FitzSimons
admits, the lending criteria will favour the traditional nuclear family with
two children against young adults without family commitments.
There appear to be good financial reasons. Mr Fitz-Simons says the society
has found unmarried couples are 50 per cent more likely to fall into arrears
than married ones.
Even so, the society was forced somewhat on to the defensive yesterday.
After the disclosure, it issued a statement saying that any scheme 'will
have to be broadly acceptable in the mortgage marketplace', and young
families with special needs would be 'properly catered for'.
Ms Jean Eaglesham, head of money policy at the Consumers Association, said
she accepted the principle of pricing for risk. However, she was concerned
that the society might breach the Sex Discrimination Act.
The second obstacle is that the pricing policy depends on past patterns of
behaviour continuing in the future. As Mr Melville-Ross of Nationwide puts
it: 'The experience of the past three years may be all that we have got to
go on, but it is not an ideal way of judging what will happen.'
The accuracy of Bristol &amp; West's pricing will depend on whether there has
been a long-term term shift in behaviour, or whether the late 1980s was a
blip. Mr FitzSimons argues that there has been a broad change in risk: 'We
are finding a lot of 'won't pays' as well as 'can't pays',' he says.
The final obstacle is whether the policy even makes sense for Bristol &amp;
West. Mr FitzSimons says
he regards with equanimity the prospect of high-risk borrowers taking
business elsewhere.
Yet Bristol &amp; West is burdened not only with bad debts but with an expensive
network of branches. Its cost-to-income ratio last year was 55.5 per cent -
the seventh-highest of the top 25 societies.
To keep the network profitable, he must keep new business flowing in what
will be a subdued mortgage market.
So there is some way to go before the mortgage market segments into pricing
according to demographic status. But whatever the outcome, it seems clear
that today's young adults will have to pay for the financial sins of their
carefree predecessors.
</TEXT>
