<HEADLINE>
FT  04 DEC 92 / Ceiling on fees recommended to curb garrulous barristers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DEFENDANTS and their lawyers may face heavy fines unless they disclose more
of their strategies in advance to judges, a consultation paper on ways to
shorten criminal trials suggests.
The paper, published yesterday, is by a working party set up by the Lord
Chancellor to consider reforms after cases such as the year-long Blue Arrow
trial.
Other ideas canvassed are to increase the powers of judges, introduce time
limits for trials and to pay lawyers fixed fees to discourage over-wordy
barristers.
A controversial measure suggested that judges should be given more powers to
order greater defence disclosure. 'Inadequate defence disclosure is seen by
many practitioners as a basic problem adding to the length of trials,' the
report says.
One option, it suggests, would be to order defendants to reveal a statement
of their cases in as much detail as the prosecution with a line-by-line
rebuttal of the case against them.
Sanctions for failing to make such disclosures might include financial
penalties on defendants and their lawyers and prevention of some
cross-examination of witnesses.
Other factors identified by the working group as responsible for over-long
trials include: the failure to identify key issues; inadequate procedural
rules; over-long indictments; verbose barristers; and the lack of a judge's
powers to control proceedings.
The report does not cover those issues relating to fraud trials being
considered by the Royal Commission on Criminal Justice, such as replacing
juries with tribunals, creating a general offence of fraud and introducing a
formal plea-bargaining system. Some defence lawyers yesterday expressed
concern that the report's suggestions, if implemented, might strengthen the
hand of prosecutors at the expense of defendants.
'This is the thin end of the wedge again,' said one QC, comparing the
suggestion for greater defence disclosure to the ending of the right to
silence for people interviewed by the Serious Fraud Office. Another
suggested that the failure of prosecutors to bring sharply focused cases
remained the main cause of over-long trials.
The report acknowledges the importance of prosecutors in ensuring trials
remain manageable, saying they bear the primary responsibility for deciding
the eventual shape and length of a case.
It criticises the Serious Fraud Office and Crown Prosecution Service for
past failures in not properly monitoring the effectiveness of barristers
they employed, although it notes that more attention is now being paid to
this.
The report, questioning whether trial judges have enough powers to manage
proceedings effectively, suggests that they should be allowed to set time
limits for the whole or parts of trials. It acknowledges that that would be
a 'radical departure from present practice' and admits strong arguments
exist against such a move.
Drawing on suggestions by Mr Justice Henry, the judge in charge of the first
two Guinness trials, it suggests the power of judges to exclude evidence
could be increased, as it is in the American federal legal system.
Consultation Paper on Long Criminal Trials. Lord Chancellor's Department.
Trevelyn House, 30, Gt Peter St, London SW1.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
