<HEADLINE>
FT  04 DEC 92 / Housing market uncertain
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S two largest building societies disagreed yesterday over whether
house prices were still falling or had started to rise after the latest
mortgage interest rate cuts.
Halifax, the country's largest society, with about a fifth of the mortgage
market, reported that house prices had risen by 0.1 per cent last month, the
first monthly increase recorded by the society since June.
Nationwide, its nearest rival, said prices had fallen on average by 2 per
cent in November, the second-largest monthly fall reported by the society
since October 1991.
The sharp difference between the monthly price surveys conducted by the
societies illustrates the uncertainty in the housing market after sterling's
withdrawal from the ERM in September.
Nationwide said yesterday: 'The number of transactions is very low at the
moment, so any movement tends to be exaggerated. It is very difficult,
therefore, to draw any firm conclusion from a single month's figures.'
Nationwide's survey was completed on November 23 while Halifax recorded
price movements until the end of the month. Indications from builders are
that sales, after a slow start to the month, picked up during the final week
of November, which may explain some of the difference between the two
societies' findings.
Halifax and Nationwide said that it would take time for the recent
reductions in interest rates to have an impact on the housing market.
Prospective buyers, they said, continued to be concerned about rising
unemployment and the state of the UK economy.
Halifax said: 'We would expect volume sales to increase by about 15 per cent
next year, in line with recent forecasts. Prices are much more difficult to
forecast and predictions range from another small fall to a small rise next
year. We would, however, expect prices to have begun to stabilise by the
second half of next year.'
</TEXT>
