<HEADLINE>
FT  04 DEC 92 / Hopes for EC breakthrough: UK plan to end Danish Maastricht
block - Summit prospects improve
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Foreign and Political Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PROSPECTS for a break in the deadlock over the European Community's future
brightened last night following a UK initiative to resolve Danish objections
to the Maastricht treaty and a Franco-German agreement on EC enlargement.
The moves, which boosted hopes for a successful EC summit in Edinburgh next
week, could clear the way for the 12 to overcome other hurdles such as the
financing of the Community.
Britain's proposals, allowing Denmark to remain outside key areas of the
treaty such as monetary union and defence, were given a cautious welcome by
other EC members. The plan, submitted by Mr John Major to the UK's partners
after a tour of EC capitals, does not tamper with the treaty's text, on the
insistence of all 12 member states. The treaty can only come into force if
ratified by the 12.
At a bilateral summit in Bonn, Mr Helmut Kohl, the German Chancellor, and
President Francois Mitterrand of France, agreed that negotiations on the
EC's enlargement should start at the beginning of next year and be concluded
by the end of 1993.
That has always been a top priority of the British and German governments.
Until yesterday, however, the French had been indicating they would not
agree to an opening of membership negotiations with new candidates until the
treaty was ratified by all existing members. However, a senior French
official warned that the negotiations could still be held up by a failure to
reach a compromise on the EC's future budget, including an increase in
so-called 'cohesion' funds for the poorer southern member states.
France's reaction to the British plan for Denmark was also cautiously
positive. Mr Jean Musitelli, President Mitterrand's spokesman, said in Bonn:
'We consider that there is a possibility of satisfying the demands presented
by the Danish government to its 11 partners by adopting adequate
declarations.'
Until now, France has been suspicious that a Danish compromise could water
down the treaty. Mr Poul Schlueter, the Danish prime minister, said the
British blueprint was 'an excellent starting point for arriving at a
satisfactory solution'.
But the opposition Social Democrats, Denmark's largest party, were less
enthusiastic. 'We consider the British proposals as a constructive draft
only,' Mr Poul Nyrup Rasmussen, the party's leader said, after a meeting of
the three main opposition parties.
The British plan provides for three separate 'clarifying' declarations which
would allow Denmark to submit the treaty to a second referendum next year,
probably in May or June.
A first statement would underline the EC's commitment to 'subsidiarity' and
greater openness in decision-making.
A second declaration would be made by the Danish government on its
interpretation of special areas of concern in the treaty. In effect, Denmark
would be permitted to establish its own legal criteria for the extension of
EC competence to areas such as citizenship and justice.
A third declaration, by all 12 states, would be designed to interpret the
treaty's provisions on defence, monetary union, citizenship and interior and
justice matters in a way which would reassure the Danish electorate.
Details, Page 2
Editorial Comment, Page 20
Joe Rogaly, Page 21
</TEXT>
