<HEADLINE>
FT  03 DEC 92 / Parliament and Politics: Labour presses PM on growth debate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR yesterday stepped up its charges that the government has backtracked
on its pledges to use the Edinburgh summit to promote a Europe-wide growth
strategy.
At a news conference Mr Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor, produced
documents allegedly confirming that Mr John Major's commitment to debate
economic expansion were in reality 'minimalist' and 'insubstantial'.
The papers included a confidential Conservative Research Department briefing
note that relegated talks at Edinburgh on economic expansion to the eighth
and last place on the agenda.
The second was the British presidency's compromise proposal for last
Friday's meeting of foreign and finance ministers on community financing.
That confined the discussion to noting that the European Investment Bank was
considering creating a new financial instrument to promote transport
networks and small and medium-sized businesses.
Backing a warning yesterday from Mr Henning Christophersen, EC economics
commissioner, that the economic outlook was grave, Mr Brown said Mr Major
should take up the scheme for an Ecu5bn (Pounds 4.02bn) European Investment
Fund.
He dismissed as inadequate the UK's proposals that fellow EC partners should
adopt measures similar to its Autumn Statement on spending which sought to
promote capital spending while reining in public-sector pay rises.
A senior Conservative official close to the Edinburgh planning process
indicated last night, however, that the government was looking for little
more than useful language on growth from the summit.
Downing Street has made clear that discussion on growth is likely to be
confined to talks over lunch.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 10
</PAGE>
