FT  03 DEC 92 / International Company News: Centel awaits takeover approval
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CENTEL, the Chicago-based telecommunications group, said yesterday that it
was confident its shareholders had approved a controversial plan for the
business to be taken over by Sprint, the third-largest US long-distance
telephone company, in a Dollars 3bn deal.
Centel investors held a special meeting yesterday to vote on the deal, which
stirred up strong opposition from some shareholders when it was announced
last May.
The results of the vote will not be announced officially until December 11.
Many large shareholders registered their votes by proxy ahead of the
gathering, and Mr John Frazee, Centel's chairman, said: 'We're confident
that, when the votes are counted, based on proxies received to date, that
the merger will be ap-proved.'
The takeover involves Centel shareholders receiving 1.37 shares of Sprint
stock for every Centel share.
On the basis of Sprint's closing price yesterday of Dollars 25 7/8 , down
Dollars  1/8 , that values each Centel share at around Dollars 35 1/2 .
Centel closed unchanged at Dollars 33 7/8 .
However, Centel shares were trading at over Dollars 42 before last May's
announcement, and some shareholders argued at yesterday's meeting that the
company was being sold on the cheap and would do better to remain as an
independent provider of local and cell-ular telecommunications ser-vices.
However, Mr Frazee replied that the recent deal under which American
Telephone &amp; Telegraph, the biggest US long-distance telephone group, will
acquire a 33 per cent stake in McCaw Cellular, the largest cellular
telephone service, 'validates the price' of the Sprint offer.
