FT  03 DEC 92 / UK-China relations 'worst for years'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT MAUTHNER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR Percy Cradock, the former policy adviser to both Lady Thatcher and Mr
John Major, the prime minister, warned last night that the present crisis in
British-Chinese relations over Hong Kong was the worst for many years.
To find such tension in relations between the two countries it would be
necessary to go back to the days of the cultural revolution in China in the
1960s, he indicated on BBC television's Newsnight programme.
Referring to Beijing's threat to revoke any contracts concluded in Hong Kong
before sovereignty over the colony reverts to China in 1997, if they have
not got China's approval, Sir Percy said the Chinese meant precisely what
they said. 'To discount their seriousness would be a very great mistake.'
Sir Percy, a former British ambassador to Beijing, said it was a fallacy to
believe that China was bluffing and that it would change its tune because of
economic considerations.
'This is a matter of national pride for them. They will not give way.'
Nor did Sir Percy think that if a more liberal regime came to power in China
there would be any change in its opposition to the democratic reforms
proposed by Mr Chris Patten, the Hong Kong governor, which are believed to
be the cause of Beijing's present anti-British campaign.
The Foreign Office said last night that nothing that Sir Percy had said
could invalidate Mr Patten's proposals.
Officials stressed that these were no more than proposals and that Hong Kong
and the British government were still waiting for the Chinese to make
counter-proposals if they did not like Mr Patten's reforms.
</TEXT>
