FT  03 DEC 92 / UN agree resolution to send forces under US command to
Somalia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   THE UN, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE UN Security Council agreed last night on a resolution to send a
multinational force under US command to Somalia to disarm warring clans and
ensure food aid gets through to the starving, reports Michael Littlejohns at
the UN in New York.
After private consultations, western diplomats said a text drafted by the US
appeared certain to be approved at a Security Council meeting today. China
is expected to abstain.
About 20,000 US troops could take part in the operation. Heeding African and
other third world objections to an overriding role for American troops, the
US apparently agreed to accept a substantial degree of UN control.
Under the terms of the draft resolution, UN Secretary General Boutros
Boutros Ghali would have a liaison staff at the force's field headquarters
in Somalia and a Security Council commission would monitor the operation.
Mr Boutros Ghali would advise the council when he believed a 'secure
environment' for humanitarian aid had been created. Normal UN peacekeeping
would then take over from the US-led operation.
The Indian president of the Security Council said the US-led intervention
would not involve financial cost to the UN.
