<HEADLINE>
FT  03 DEC 92 / Commodities and Agriculture: Bad weather dampens US maize
hopes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURIE MORSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CHICAGO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
COLD, WET weather and early snow storms ended the maize harvest prematurely
in some parts of the upper midwest last week, and set market bulls in
Chicago talking about quality problems that could reduce the size of the
bumper crop.
However, state agronomists and crop analysts say the quality problems are
localised. The US maize crop is so large, and the quality of harvested grain
is so high, that there is little chance that the US Department of
Agriculture's estimate of a 9.33bn bushel crop will be revised downward by
more than a few million bushels.
The USDA next reports preliminary crop estimates on December 10. Final
numbers on the US maize harvest will be released in January.
Still, high moisture content in much of the nation's maize crop will require
costly drying and special handling, trimming grower's profits. And in
scattered areas, high moisture and a short growing season have lowered test
weights and generated mould growth - a condition that leaves the maize unfit
for export or livestock consumption.
'What we have is an abundance of good quality corn (maize) nationally, and
an abundance of low quality corn in small areas,' says Mr David Miller, an
Illinois-based American Farm Bureau analyst.
The US maize harvest is usually complete by the end of November. However,
about 7m bushels, or about 20 per cent of the crop, is still standing in the
fields in Iowa and Illinois, the biggest maize-producing states. About 30
per cent of Indiana's maize crop is still in the field. Most of that grain
will eventually be harvested, although farmers might wait until mid-winter
freezes make the muddy fields safe for combines. In the meantime, the grain
will be subject to moisture and mold.
The situation in northern states is more severe. Only half of Wisconsin's
maize crop has been cut, and in Michigan, three quarters of the acreage is
awaiting harvest. Those states were projected to harvest about 500m bushels,
with more than half grown for on-farm livestock feed.
Much of that crop will not be harvested. Green, or underdeveloped, kernels
and mold have reduced the value of the maize there. County officials report
that farmers are plowing some fields under, or chopping the maize for
silage. 'Very little of our corn is intended to be abandoned, but a lot may
end up that way,' says a farm agent from Wisconsin's Sauk County.
</TEXT>
