<HEADLINE>
FT  03 DEC 92 / Government Bonds: Gilts tumble following disappointing
auction
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SARA WEBB and PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
UK GOVERNMENT bonds fell a quarter-point after the Bank of England's
disappointing auction of government bonds.
The Bank offered Pounds 2.5bn of a newly-created stock, the 8 per cent gilt
due 2003, which is expected to take over as the new 10-year benchmark gilt.
However, demand for the stock was poor: the Bank reported a cover ratio (the
ratio of bids to the amount on offer) of only 1.26 times, and the auction
was dominated by domestic players as foreign investors continued to shy away
from the gilt market.
The lowest accepted price was 96 13/16 , to yield 8.48 per cent, while the
highest accepted price was 96 15/16 , yielding 8.46 per cent. The spread of
bids was relatively narrow, as dealers pointed out that it was not difficult
to price the new gilt.
'The bids were very tightly grouped around the market level', said Mr John
Shepperd, economist at S. G. Warburg Securities.
The auction was the first since sterling left the European exchange rate
mechanism in September. Foreign investors have been reluctant to invest in
gilts since then because of the greater exchange rate risk, and were largely
absent from yesterday's auction. Both domestic and foreign investors have
become concerned about the heavy funding pressures on the market and the
possibility of rising inflation.
Dealers said that quite a lot of the auction stock ended up with
marketmakers, and warned that this could overhang the market for a while.
GERMAN government bonds ended weaker as the Bundesbank emphasised its
commitment to low inflation, wiping out any hopes of lower German interest
rates.
In addition, the new issue of bonds from Treuhand, the privatisation agency,
had a poor reception which further depressed the bund market.
The Liffe bund futures contract fell from its opening 91.03 to a low of
90.71 on around 45,000 contracts.
The fall in bund prices followed comments from Mr Helmut Schlesinger, the
Bundesbank president, that Germany should not give up its tight monetary
policies to fall in with the wishes of other European countries.
The Treuhand agency yesterday allocated DM 4.05bn of its new ten-year 7 3/8
per cent bonds in a tender. The minimum accepted price was 99.51, and the
average was 99.54, for a yield of 7.44 per cent.
JAPANESE government bonds closed higher on expectations of a cut in interest
rates. The benchmark No 145 opened with a yield of 4.605 per cent and
climbed steadily all day, to close at 4.58 per cent.
The rate on three-month certificates of deposit fell from 3.8 per cent to
3.75 per cent, encouraging hopes that the Bank of Japan may cut the Official
Discount Rate this month. Dealers said the passage of the supplementary
budget in Japan's lower house added to the bullish mood.
US TREASURY prices were mixed across the maturity range yesterday as dealers
and investors traded cautiously ahead of today's all-important November
employment report.
In late trading the benchmark 30-year government bond was down  1/32 at 100
21/32 , yielding 7.564 per cent. But prices were slightly firmer at the
short end of the market with the two-year note up  1/32 at 99 5/8 , to yield
4.808 per cent.
Eyes were focused on jobs data due this morning. Recent statistics have
painted a picture of gradual recovery, but the employment report should give
the best indication yet of economic conditions. Economists expect a rise of
about 50,000 in non-farm payrolls.
Nervousness ahead of the figures partially explained the slight reaction to
the 10.3 per cent plunge in home sales in October. But the chief reason for
indifference was the unreliability of home sales data, and the fact that the
big drop in October was offset by an upward revision for September.
