FT  03 DEC 92 / International Company News: Brazilian chocolate maker
tumbles to Cr40bn deficit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BILL HINCHBERGER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAO PAULO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
LACTA, the market leader in Brazilian chocolates, suffered a loss of
Cr40.4bn (Dollars 5.6m) for the first nine months of 1992. In 1991, the
company earned Dollars 1.5m for the entire year.
The Brazilian chocolate market has fallen by 15 per cent this year, but
Lacta said it managed to hold the company's decline to 12 per cent.
Lacta is one of Brazil's big three chocolate makers. It enjoyed a 43 per
cent market share for January-July, compared with 28 per cent for Nestle,
the subsidiary of the Swiss multinational, and 24.6 per cent for Garoto, a
Brazilian competitor.
A dispute has been simmering between the controlling group, headed by
Brazilian businessman Mr Adhemar de Barros Filho, and minority partner
Jacobs Suchard, the Swiss company owned by Philip Morris. Jacobs Suchard
held 40 per cent of voting capital before it was purchased by Philip Morris.
Earlier this year, a planned stock issue was held up by a judicial
restraining order sought by Jacobs Suchard. Lacta is now authorised to make
the issue, but no date has been set.
