FT  03 DEC 92 / International Company News: Seagram 9% lower as marketing
costs rise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MONTREAL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE RECESSION continued to dampen Seagram's wine and spirits business in the
third quarter, while the Tropicana fruit juice unit performed strongly and
benefited from lower overheads.
Third-quarter net profit was USDollars 178m, or 47 cents a share, down 9 per
cent from Dollars 193m, or 51 cents a share, a year earlier.
Mr Edgar Bronfman Jr, president, said in a statement that the Canadian
group's flat performance in the third quarter was due mainly to the
recession's impact on several key global markets, but also to higher
advertising outlays to support its most important brands. Seagram spends
around Dollars 500m a year on advertising worldwide.
He said: 'But we expect our overall operating income for the full year
ending January 31 will exceed the Dollars 760m reported for fiscal 1992.'
Sales from the worldwide drinks business dipped 3.7 per cent to Dollars
1.45bn following the sale of several spirits brands in the US in the final
quarter of fiscal 1991.
In the third quarter, sales from continuing operations were steady.
Operating income was Dollars 198m, against Dollars 206m.
Results included Dollars 73m in dividends from Du Pont of the US, against
Dollars 69m, and Dollars 41m equity in unremitted Du Pont earnings, against
Dollars 51m.
Net income for the nine months to October 31 was Dollars 497m, or Dollars
1.32 a share, down 6.5 per cent from Dollars 530m, or Dollars 1.40 a share,
a year earlier. Sales were Dollars 4.9bn against Dollars 4.28bn. Results
included Du Pont dividends of Dollars 214m, compared with Dollars 207m, and
unremitted earnings of Dollars 121m, against Dollars 185m.
Seagram is one of the world's top four drinks groups, selling in 150
countries and with subsidiaries and affiliates in 34 countries. Its main
expansion thrust is in Asia and Europe because of the long decline in the
North American spirits market.
