FT  03 DEC 92 / Bass's profits rise of 16.5% to Pounds 501m falls short of
expectations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP RAWSTORNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BASS, the brewing, hotels and leisure group, fell short of market
expectations yesterday in spite of a 16.5 per cent increase in full-year
pre-tax profits to Pounds 501m.
Shares fell 15p to close at 585p as Mr Ian Prosser, chairman, said he
expected no improvement in tough trading conditions before late summer next
year.
'There are signs that the American economy may be moving in the right
direction but . . . we have seen false signals in this respect in the past
two years,' he said. 'In the UK, we do not see any such signs.'
Market sentiment was further depressed by evidence of damage inflicted by
the UK recession and the government-enforced disposal of pubs.
A property revaluation has led to a write-down of Pounds 496m, 13 per cent
of total property value and about half of the surplus recorded in the 1989
revaluation.
The sale of 1,213 pubs during the year contributed to a 24.5 per cent
decline in pub operating profits but Bass recouped the lost beer volumes
with gains in the free pub trade and take-home market.
Earnings per share for the year to September 30 grew 8.3 per cent to 39.6p;
a final dividend of 13.65p raises the total payment to 18.9p, an increase of
6.2 per cent.
The accounts include exceptional charges of Pounds 75m for rationalisation
and reorganisation costs in the brewing and pub divisions; and an
extraordinary credit of Pounds 91m mainly from surpluses on pub disposals.
Group operating profit declined 1.5 per cent to Pounds 612.1m (from Pounds
622.7m) on turnover reduced from Pounds 4.38bn to Pounds 4.31bn.
Profit contribution from brewing operations rose 13.5 per cent to Pounds
210m on turnover of Pounds 1.59bn, 3.2 per cent ahead.
Volume sales to the free pub trade grew 9.8 per cent; sales to the take-home
trade rose 5.2 per cent.
Overall, volumes declined 1.7 per cent against a market fall of 2.9 per cent
and market share increased marginally.
Pub retailing profits were Pounds 57m lower at Pounds 174m after the
disposal programme, which accounted for about Pounds 40m of the reduction.
Capital expenditure on refurbishment and information systems totalled Pounds
110m.
Holiday Inn hotels achieved a 12.4 per cent increase in operating profits to
Pounds 116m.
Lex, Page 22; Details, Page 25
