<HEADLINE>
FT  03 DEC 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Those who fancy Joanna Lumley in school uniform (calm down and form an
orderly queue between London and Edinburgh) will need to watch Absolutely
Fabulous, Jennifer Saunders' comedy series set in the fashion business. So
far it has been very funny (9.00 BBC2). That is followed by a Horizon
special which will presumably get the biggest audience ever for this science
series: 'The Truth About Sex'. Cameras followed researchers as they
interviewed some of the 20,000 subjects of the National Sex Survey.
Commissioned by the government, then dropped, this has been financed by the
Wellcome Trust. Spurred by what was expected to be a forest-fire epidemic of
AIDS, the survey set out to establish what proportion of the British
population is homosexual or bisexual, and how promiscuous people are,
especially those in the high-risk categories for Aids, homosexuals and drug
addicts. In the AIDS Update 92 on ITV (10.40) dealing with AIDS in Africa it
will be interesting to see whether the broadcasters have the courage to
investigate the social and sexual reasons for the difference in the
incidence of AIDS between countries.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 19
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-4254</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CLCB9AC1FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921203
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  03 DEC 92 / Arts: My Father's Vertigo - Dance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLEMENT CRISP
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The trappings which surround Amanda Miller's My Father's Vertigo for London
Contemporary Dance Theatre - an incomprehensible title; a portentous
programme note about 'the need to dwell' - are tiresome. They reflect
something of the taste current in Frankfurt, where Miss Miller
(American-born) works with William Forsythe's company. And, as with
Forsythe's works, this obscurantism seems a ploy to disorientate the viewer.
Yet what we saw on Tuesday, when LCDT gave the piece its first London
showing, was choreography of real interest.
The score is an atmospheric string quartet by Fred Frith: music that
shimmers, is haunted by echoes and odd glissandi beneath its melodies. Miss
Miller's writing (for a cast of five men and six women: uniformly excellent)
stresses a sinuous, smoothly muscled language that can look at moments as if
action is slowed down, its fluidity almost oily, its pulse irregular as
movement slips forward and seems on the point of losing balance. As with
Forsythe's work, there is emotionally potent lighting which shifts our
perceptions about the dancers through arbitrary change. (There are also
hints of the greyness favoured in Frankfurt in the costuming of men in grey
tops, black trousers, women in grey frocks, black stockings).
The dance style is unified by its insistance on flowing activity, even if
its incidents do not at first seem to cohere. Yet as ideas are repeated,
transferred among the cast, the choreography tells of a concern with how
energy may move through a body, how muscular force is expended. The music's
second movement proposes contrasting quartets for men and women, each with
an observer watching from 'outside' the action as a dynamic and emotional
counter-weight. A later duet between Andrew Robinson and Tom Ward is a
fascinating conflict between opposing physiques. Towards the work's end, odd
activity - Kenneth Tharp indulging in mute and mimed conversation - seems
set to distort the mood. And with every switch of action, Miss Miller's
movement world remains intriguing.
Visually the piece is austere, very well lit. The spectral appearance of
what I take to be a head of a women by Titian on the grey gauze backdrop is
curious, but curiously effective. In matter of composition, My Father's
Vertigo offers a subtle sense of form and language. It is a bold addition to
the repertory, and, as I have mentioned, is danced with grand assurance by
its cast. This second LCDT programme also includes Mark Morris's Motorcade -
its dancing still not quite quick enough in musical response - and Rikud,
last's years brutish acquisition from Liat Dror and Nir Ben Gal, which I
prefer not to watch.
London Contemporary Dance Theatre is at Sadler's Wells Theatre with this
programme until December 5.
</TEXT>
