<HEADLINE>
FT  03 DEC 92 / Arms software for Iraq 'was approved'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ICL, THE UK-based computer manufacturer in which Fujitsu of Japan has a
majority stake, confirmed this week that three government departments
approved a 1989 move to supply an advanced computerised defence system to
the Iraq Ministry of Defence prior to the invasion of Kuwait.
The attempted sale, details of which are published today in the trade
newspaper Computer Weekly, is further evidence of relaxed government
attitudes towards the sale of military equipment to Iraq during the late
1980s.
ICL said yesterday that the deal, involving the ICL-developed Air Staff
Management Aid (Asma) command-and-control system - used by the allies during
the Gulf war - fell through for 'ordinary business reasons' long before the
onset of hostilities.
ICL obtained export licences for the Asma software in 1989 after detailed
discussions with the Ministry of Defence, the Foreign Office and the
Department of Trade and Industry.
</TEXT>
