<HEADLINE>
FT  03 DEC 92 / February hint for Sunday trade reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RESEARCH into the likely impact of Sunday trading reform is to be completed
by the end of next month, indicating that the government may decide to press
ahead with the proposed bill as early as February.
The research will form the basis of a study on the financial impact of the
three reform proposals that the government plans to include in the bill.
The analysis will be set out in an explanatory paper that the government has
promised to publish before the proposed legislation has its second Commons
reading.
Mr Kenneth Clarke, home secretary, told Tory MPs last week they would be
offered a free vote on the three options, which range from full deregulation
of Sunday trading in England and Wales to a tightening of existing laws.
According to a covering letter signed by Mr Peter Lloyd, Home Office
minister, which has been sent to retailers asked to provide information for
the survey, the analysis will be of 'the impact on costs and prices, and on
employment and trading patterns' of each option.
London Economics, the company commissioned to conduct the research, is
seeking information from every retailer with an annual turnover of more than
Pounds 12m and from more than 250 single-outlet shops.
The timing of the study suggests that its results will not be available in
time for a private member's bill proposed by Labour's Mr Ray Powell. This
advocates the tightening of existing, widely flouted laws and is due to be
debated by MPs early next year.
New legislation must await a decision by the European Court on whether the
present law is overridden by the free-trade articles of the Treaty of Rome.
Mr Clarke said last week that the ruling was unlikely to be available before
next month. He made clear that work on getting the bill ready would proceed
before the EC judgment.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
