<HEADLINE>
FT  03 DEC 92 / Parliament and Politics: Civil Service agencies to grow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THREE QUARTERS of the Civil Service is set to have become 'next steps'
agencies, operating at arm's length from central government departments by
mid 1995.
But the annual report on the agencies, published yesterday, makes clear that
the government expects there to be little scope for creating further
agencies beyond that.
The most substantial - and controversial - of the 29 new candidates already
identified for agency status is the prison service, which employs some
38,000 staff.
Agencies already include parts of government that vary from Companies House
to the forensic science service, but the next wave of new agencies will
broaden that range even further, to include, for example, royal parks and
the meat hygiene service.
The planned timescale is that all candidates for agency status, perhaps a
further 30 to 50 beyond those already identified, should have been agreed
for change by the end of next year, and have been set up within the
following 18 months.
Announcing the report, Mr William Waldegrave, the public service minister,
said that half the Civil Service - about 300,000 people - were already
working in agencies, and that 'we are beginning to see real improvements in
efficiency, productivity and value for money.'
The document shows that about three in four of the performance targets, some
of which have become harder since last year, were met by the agencies in
1991-92. That average covers a wide variation in performance among the 76
individual agencies.
The acceptance by the government that there is a ceiling on which government
activities can be turned into agencies reflects a mood among those dealing
with the changes in Whitehall that ministers believe that future emphasis
should lie with market-testing and contracting out.
The Next Steps Agencies - Review 1992, HMSO, Pounds 13.30.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
