<HEADLINE>
FT  03 DEC 92 / Accountants approve strict ethical rules
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ACCOUNTANCY FIRMS will not be able to conduct specialist valuations for
their audit clients under strict ethical guidelines approved yesterday.
Firms will also be required to contact the existing auditor if they are
approached by a company to provide a second opinion on an accounting
standard, the council of the Institute of Chartered Accountants in England
and Wales said.
The two guidance notes, which come into force on February 1, were introduced
by the Chartered Accountants Joint Ethics Committee, representing the
English Institute and its equivalents in Scotland and Ireland.
Their ratification follows several months of consultation. Only one of the
leading six accounting firms - believed to be Coopers &amp; Lybrand - opposed
the specialist valuations guideline.
The note aims to remove any apparent threat to objectivity of the audit by
preventing auditors providing actuarial valuations, or valuations of other
assets such as intellectual property, brands, other intangible assets,
property and unquoted investments.
The note on second opinions or 'opinion shopping' is designed to prevent
companies hunting for support from the profession when their auditor refuses
to approve a particular accounting treatment.
It ensures that the second firm approached possesses the full information
available to the company's auditor before it passes judgment.
The council also yesterday voted to approve additional openness in its
disciplinary hearings. It ratified suggestions for greater disclosure of
judgments, but has stalled proposals that would lead to open hearings on
matters of public interest.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
