<HEADLINE>
FT  03 DEC 92 / Cadbury may add to audit fees
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE SCRUTINY of companies' compliance with the Cadbury code of corporate
governance may add at least 10 per cent to audit fees, a leading accountant
said yesterday.
Meanwhile, the Department of Trade and Industry confirmed that it will be
considering the changes in the law recommended by the Cadbury committee.
The details came as executives and professionals digested the final
recommendations of the committee on the financial aspects of corporate
governance, chaired by Sir Adrian Cadbury, which were published on Tuesday.
The Cadbury committee said that all quoted companies will be required as
part of the Stock Exchange's listing requirements to make a statement in
their annual reports from next June that they comply with the code, or state
where they differ from it. The committee also recommended that auditors
should also be required to ensure that a company's statement is accurate.
Mr Roger Davis, head of audit at Coopers &amp; Lybrand, the accountancy firm,
said the additional audit fee for conducting this service might be 10 per
cent to 15 per cent, although he emphasised that this had to contrasted with
the sharp reductions in audit fees over the past few years.
The Cadbury committee focused on issues of best practice, but also
recommended three changes in the law: that audit and non-audit fees paid by
a company to its auditor should be clearly disclosed in the accounts; that
statutory protection to report fraud should be provided to auditors of all
companies; and that directors' contracts should be limited to three years
without shareholder approval.
Mr Nigel Hamilton, minister for corporate affairs, said: 'The fundamental
issue is raising professional business standards rather than regulation.'
But he added he would now 'carefully consider the recommendations addressed
to government'.
The DTI said that greater disclosure of auditors' fee could be introduced
through a statutory instrument. The other two changes would require primary
legislation, which would be considered as part of the comprehensive review
of the 1985 Companies Act it announced last month.
The auditing profession had made strong representations to the Cadbury
committee, arguing that it would not be feasible to scrutinise the code to
ensure that companies were complying.
Mr Bill Morrison, chairman of the Auditing Practices Board, which will
produce guidelines on auditing the code, said yesterday that it would be
feasible to audit the more limited, quantifiable aspects of the code
highlighted in the final version of the report.
</TEXT>
