<HEADLINE>
FT  03 DEC 92 / Rise in reserves surprises City
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UK'S official gold and foreign currency reserves rose an underlying
Dollars 86m last month. The figures, released by the Treasury yesterday,
surprised City economists, who had forecast another fall.
In September and October the reserves fell quite sharply, reflecting heavy
spending by the Bank of England on September 16 in a vain attempt to prop up
the pound.
The official reserve figures are not necessarily a good guide to official
intervention on the foreign exchanges. The Bank is able to shroud
intervention levels by borrowing on the foreign exchange forward market.
Those loans can be rolled over indefin-itely.
The Bank also made borrowings from other European central banks before Black
Wednesday, which do not have to be paid back until the middle of December.
Mr John Shepperd, economist at SG Warburgs Securities, said: 'The rise of
Dollars 86m tells us nothing about what has been going on in terms of
intervention. To look to the official reserves for guidance is a lost
cause.'
The underlying change excludes a number of factors, such as Ecu Treasury
bill proceeds. The Treasury figures showed that the overall level of the
reserves fell by Dollars 51m, bringing the total to Dollars 42.09bn at the
end of November, compared with Dollars 42.14bn at the end of October.
Analysts believe that the full amount spent by the Bank in mid September may
not be known until the middle of next year.
</TEXT>
