FT  03 DEC 92 / Scrapping Thorp plant 'may cost Pounds 3bn'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CANCELLATION of British Nuclear Fuel's plans for reprocessing nuclear waste
may cost Britain up to Pounds 3bn, the director in charge of the project
said yesterday.
Mr David Bonser, director of BNF's Thorp plant at Sellafield, said Britain
would lose Pounds 900m in future earnings from overseas, and the state-owned
company or government might have to pay back 'a good whack' of the Pounds
2bn foreign customers paid in advance if the Pounds 2.8bn plant was
abandoned.
'There's no question that millions of pounds would be due under contracts
with customers,' Mr Bonser said - and possibly all of it, depending on the
outcome of legal action. BNF said that if Thorp did not go ahead Sellafield
would shut after 10 years when present contracts ended.
Mr Bonser said Her Majesty's Inspectorate of Pollution had told BNF that
there were no 'safety, technical, or waste management reasons' why the plant
should not start operation.
The Thorp plant, which has taken 10 years to build, was due to start
processing spent nuclear fuel from nuclear reactors in the UK and overseas
within two weeks.
The start of operations has been on hold since a delay in authorising new
levels of radioactive emissions by the inspectorate. BNF fears the
inspectorate's two-month public consultation period, ending mid January,
might be followed by a public inquiry lasting months. That might jeopardise
the future of the plant. Mr Bonser said Touche Ross, the consultancy firm,
had calculated that if Thorp were abandoned Britain would lose Pounds 900m
in future earnings from overseas customers, after taking into account
Thorp's running costs.
Britain might have to compensate foreign customers for the change of plans,
and would be obliged to send back the 2,500 tonnes of foreign radioactive
fuel
Cancelling such an expensive high-technology project has so far appeared
politically unthinkable.
</TEXT>
