<HEADLINE>
FT  03 DEC 92 / Reform of credit-card law urged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
URGENT REFORM of the law covering credit cards is needed to clear up
uncertainties about the protection offered to consumers who use credit cards
to buy goods or services that turn out to be defective, the Law Society,
which represents solicitors, said yesterday.
A cardholder who buys a ticket from an airline that collapses before the
ticket has been used can recover the cost of the ticket from the card issuer
under the terms of the 1974 Consumer Credit Act.
For goods or services costing between Pounds 100 and Pounds 30,000 the act
gives cardholders the same legal rights for breach of contract or
misrepresentation against the issuer of the card as the seller.
The society says in many situations it is now uncertain whether the
protection exists. The most common is where there is no direct link in the
form of a contract between the card issuer and the seller.
That occurs because most retailers now have a single payment-handling
agreement with one card issuer, which handles all card payments to the
retailer for all other card issuers.
Where another card issuer's card is used there are four parties to the
transaction: the card issuer; the retailer; the issuer handling payments;
and the cardholder.
The 1974 act was designed to cover only three party transactions -
debtor/creditor/supplier agreements. It is not clear whether it applies to
transactions involving four parties. Card issuers say it does not.
Another area of uncertainty relates to use of credit cards abroad. The
society says no one knows whether protection is limited to transactions in
the UK. It says consumers can find the protection they thought they had does
not exist. That leads to resentment and distress and costly disputes with
card issuers.
The society says reform is urgently needed to ensure the law provides the
protection it was designed to give.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
