<HEADLINE>
FT  03 DEC 92 / No appeal for tax rebellion in Epsom
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS and ARIANE GENILLARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
STORIES of council tax chaos and imminent rebellion in the Home Counties are
wildly exaggerated, if yesterday's placid atmosphere in Epsom Town Hall is
any indication.
With council tax bandings just released, few residents who dropped in to
find out their band were either clamouring to appeal or furious at their
likely average bill of Pounds 620, which is less than the average houshold
is paying in poll tax.
'If you think about it, councils need the same amount of money as before, so
we won't escape it', was a typical response, voiced by Mr Charles Jarman,
who paid Pounds 95,000 for a house now worth Pounds 88,000. Like most
others, he does not intend to appeal, although his house has been put in
Band E, which starts at Pounds 88,000.
The borough's treasurer, Mr Trevor Willington, is relaxed about the public
response.
He said: 'There will obviously be appeals, but people can't appeal until
next April, after they get their bills, and when they realise that the gap
between the central bands is not much over Pounds 100, I doubt we'll have
too much fuss.'
The Borough of Epsom and Ewell is a fair barometer of the south-east,
outside London. Its northern parts - including Worcester Park, where Mr John
Major grew up - are outer suburbia, mostly band D (Pounds 68,000-Pounds
88,000) territory. Move south towards the green belt and band E and F
properties abound. Few households are at the extremes - the borough has just
57 properties in band A and 120 in band H.
Most residents calling at the town hall seemed happy with the council tax
and their banding. Even the disgruntled ones were unsure whether to appeal.
Mr Patrick Webb, a sales director with a Pounds 60,000 flat, said: 'It's a
Catch-22 situation. If you try to get your property into a lower band, it
may backfire when you try to sell it.'
One council officer said she would 'certainly' appeal against her own band F
(Pounds 120,000 to Pounds 160,000) valuation for a house bought for Pounds
115,000 in November 1987, but said: 'I am very surprised one cannot appeal
until April '93. I guess the thought is that a lot of people will have
cooled off before then.'
Mr Willington said he was 'struck that most people are finding themselves on
the band they expected'. The council was not using council tax to boost
spending but was anxious to move down to the government's assessment of what
it should be spending. It was planning to reduce its budget from Pounds 6m
to Pounds 5.6m.
A pensioner caught the Epsom mood: 'The poll tax was shocking. Now they have
swung the other way, but you will never find a truly fair system.'
</TEXT>
