<HEADLINE>
FT  03 DEC 92 / Commissions for brokers falling
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE amount of commissions paid to UK stockbrokers is continuing to fall,
even though the commission rates they charge have stabilised in recent
years, according to research published by the London Stock Exchange
yesterday.
The exchange's latest annual survey of the costs of share trading in the UK
shows that far more trades are being carried out net (free of commission).
Also, many involve part of the commission being refunded to the investor -
known as 'soft commission' arrangements.
Nearly a third of all trades by value do not involve the payment of any
commissions at all, the exchange's research shows.
That is up from around a quarter in 1991. Soft commissions, meanwhile,
account for 12 per cent to 13 per cent of stock exchange turnover, according
to industry estimates quoted in the research.
Institutional investors are negotiating more actively to make sure they get
keener prices when trading - eating into the profits of market-makers.
About 55 per cent of trades worth more than Pounds 100,000 are conducted
inside the 'touch', or quoted price, pointing to negotiation over the price.
For overseas equity trades, 60 per cent more are done inside the touch.
The average commission rate paid by institutions, meanwhile, was 0.24 per
cent, down marginally from the 0.26 per cent in 1991 but close to the
average level of around 0.25 per cent paid since 1988.
The research, to be published next week in the exchange's quarterly review,
shows that overseas investors and individuals have become less active
traders since the end of 1980s.
Overseas investors now account for 11 per cent of UK equity turnover, half
what it was two years ago, while individual investors' share of trading has
fallen from a high of 27 per cent in the 1980s to 14 per cent.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-4306</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CLCB9ABLFT</PROFILE>
