<HEADLINE>
FT  03 DEC 92 / Bundesbank's whispers turn to shouts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE guardians of the D-Mark have forsaken their traditional low-key
communications techniques. The masters of the Delphic mumble have taken
instead to shouting their message from the rooftops.
Mr Helmut Schlesinger, Bundesbank president, and his partners on the bank's
council have found new confidence. In a series of speeches they have spelt
out with uncommon and increasing clarity the failings of German financial
and economic policies, and at the same time exposed the potholes in the road
to European monetary union.
The Bundesbank has taken advantage of the confusion and uncertainty
paralysing European Community politics and disrupting money markets. After
absorbing intense and fierce criticism of its policies for almost two years,
it feels the time has come to do more than repeatedly defend its rigid
stance and has sprung on to the offensive.
Irritated by impertinent foreign demands for interest rate cuts, the bank
has started shooting back at the politicians making them. It has also
successfully off-loaded the responsibility for its rigid monetary stance on
to Bonn.
Mr Schlesinger's campaigning reached a new high on Tuesday when he announced
that mechanisms designed to keep the European monetary system stable did not
work. The obligation on central banks to intervene in support of weaker
currencies within the exchange rate mechanism was little more than an
invitation for speculators, he said.
The bank is estimated to have lost more than DM1bn (Pounds 400m) during
recent fruitless battles to defend sterling and the lira, and was
intervening again yesterday as the French franc came under strain.
President Schlesinger underlined his concerns by repeating a blast from a
speech made 10 days earlier. Then he proclaimed that the economic
convergence criteria governing the transition to a common currency were
neither clear nor tough enough. Without changes, monetary union could be
infected with the deadly inflation virus from the outset. While still
insisting that there is no need for fundamental reforms, the bank has
succinctly imparted how little it thinks of politicians' attempts at
monetary engineering.
Although Bonn appeared to have accepted that priority should be given to
cutting subsidies rather than shuffling the numbers, Mr Schlesinger is still
waiting for signs of the drastic economies urged by Chancellor Kohl's own
independent advisers.
Apart from higher short-term borrowing, anathema to the bank, the government
had not yet found a way to share out the costs of unification, he said. If a
solution was not found the issue would be resolved through higher taxes or
higher inflation. 'We can take it for granted that no-one wants the latter.'
In this week's speech he also opened up with unaccustomed vigour on
politicians who had the nerve to exert 'moral pressure' on the Bundesbank to
cut interest rates while it was still battling to win the war against German
inflation. He made plain that if politicians wanted to help stabilise
markets and reduce money market speculators' room for manoeuvre, they would
be better advised to stop regarding exchange rates as tokens of political
prestige and give their central banks independence. The sort of pressure
exerted on the Bundesbank of late actually increased doubts about Emu,
claimed the man who has raised more than his share of grave concerns.
But he left his audience with no doubts about his stance on interest rates.
It would be a mistake, even taking into account the 'short-term problems' of
partner countries, for the Bundesbank to try to iron out domestic economic
difficulties with a lax monetary policy. That would be a disservice to
European monetary integration, he declared. With that, he dropped the
community's most gnawed-at bone of contention in Chancellor Kohl's backyard,
and stalked off back to Frankfurt.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
