<HEADLINE>
FT  03 DEC 92 / Competition cuts phone charges
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGO DIXON and ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANY TELEPHONE bills will be reduced from January after British
Telecommunications and Mercury Communications yesterday announced a series
of price changes.
Further cuts in phone bills are in prospect later next year as a result of
vigorous competition between the two telecommunication companies.
In a break with its traditional pricing policy, BT said it might reduce its
prices by more than required by Oftel, the industry regulator, in order to
persuade customers to make more calls.
The change in BT's pricing policy has been prompted by a combination of
increased competition, tighter regulation and the arrival of executives who
have experience of market driven industries. Prominent among these is Mr
Michael Hepher, group managing director, who was chairman of Lloyds Abbey
Life until last year.
BT yesterday announced a freeze on call charges, bigger discounts on its
standard rates for customers who make many calls and improved terms on its
optional pricing packages. Calls to the US and Canada will be cut by between
3 and 10 per cent. But BT said line rental charges would be increased by 5.9
per cent.
As a result of the changes, businesses will see their phone bills fall by
between 0.6 per cent and 4.1 per cent, depending on their size, BT said. But
the average residential customer's bill will rise by 2.4 per cent.
Mercury pre-empted BT's price changes by announcing improvements to its own
optional pricing packages, which it said would give customers extra savings
of 5 per cent.
Optional pricing packages are a new feature in the UK telecommunications
market which allow customers to pay cheaper call rates in exchange for
higher standing charges.
Mr Hepher said BT had more price cuts 'up our sleeve' which it did not want
to reveal for competitive reasons. According to preliminary calculations by
Oftel, BT must cut its prices on average by a further 2 per cent before the
end of next July to comply with regulations. This would reduce phone bills
by another Pounds 150m.
But Mr Hepher said BT might go further than required if it found that
customers were responding to lower call charges by increasing the use of
their phones. 'There is no doubt that prices for telephony are coming down
and the more people use the phone, the more they will come down' said Mr
Hepher.
He added that BT would be testing various measures to stimulate phone usage,
such as cheaper European calls throughout January and discounts for
customers with a second telephone at home.
Since last month it has introduced cheap calls on Sunday afternoons, which
has led to a doubling of call volumes.
The moves were generally welcomed by telephone user and consumer groups,
although some expressed concern about the increase in line rental charges
which will disproportionately fall on poorer residential customers.
BT's share price fell 4p to 414p. Cable and Wireless, which owns Mercury,
suffered a 16p fall to 643p, although much of this was accounted for by the
uncertainty in Hong Kong.
Editorial Comment, Page 20
</TEXT>
