<HEADLINE>
FT  02 DEC 92 / US-led force set to intervene in Somalia: UN approval near
as Marines are despatched
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS and GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE United Nations Security Council last night reached broad agreement on
authorising a US-led force for Somalia, while an advance party of Marines
was already heading to the starving country.
The general accord emerged from private consultations between diplomats from
the Security Council's 15 member nations.
The council is expected to vote tomorrow or Friday to despatch the force to
Somalia to make sure food gets through to the starving rather than to
looters and local warlords.
Mr Boutros Boutros Ghali, the UN secretary general, earlier indicated he
preferred a force under more direct UN control.
But Sir David Hannay, Britain's delegate, said there was 'a large degree of
support' for a multi-national force for which the country providing the
largest contingent would also provide the commander.
The Chinese delegate indicated he might abstain because Beijing preferred an
enlargement of the exisiting UN peacekeeping force in Somalia.
The advance party of 1,800 US Marines sailing to Somalia could be in
position off Mogadishu today, ready to land once the UN gives the go-ahead.
US military officials said the Marines could be used to secure airport
facilities, assisting Pakistani troops of the UN peace force already there,
and paving the way for a force of perhaps 15,000-20,000 US troops.
It is not clear how many countries might be willing to contribute
contingents to the proposed US-led force.
The prospect of using US troops in Somalia is causing considerable
trepidation in Washington, where the successful conclusion of Operation
Desert Storm last year has not wholly erased the memory of Vietnam as a
traumatic warning against military involvement in faraway countries.
Somalia does not, by any account, meet the criteria formulated by Mr Caspar
Weinberger, defence secretary under President Ronald Reagan, to guide
decisions on when to commit US forces: intervention may have the support of
the American people, but there is no substantial US national security
interest, nor is it clear what would constitute victory.
White House officials have stressed the limited goal of establishing the
conditions for food aid to start flowing again. They have played down
earlier suggestions that one of the aims would be to re-establish some kind
of Somali government in place of the warring guerrilla factions that have
made it difficult to mount any effective famine relief operation.
Military commanders appear much less worried about the prospect of
intervention in relatively flat and barren Somalia than they are about the
conflict in mountainous Bosnia, where they say outside military intervention
would stand little chance of success.
While recognising that the various Somali guerrilla bands could make life
uncomfortable, Pentagon officials believe that superior training, armaments
and air power would permit a US force to establish control quickly.
US officials said Washington told Mr Boutros Ghali last week it expected US
forces to be in Somalia for two to four months.
After that, conventional UN peacekeeping troops would be able to keep order,
possibly demobilise all Somali factions and smooth the way for a functioning
government in place of the virtual anarchy now prevailing.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 5
</PAGE>
