<HEADLINE>
FT  02 DEC 92 / Brazil calls off talks with IMF
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTINA LAMB
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   RIO DE JANEIRO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BRAZIL has called off crucial talks with the International Monetary Fund
because of 'uncertainties over economic policy'.
The planning and economy ministers and central bank governor had been due to
leave for Washington on Saturday to try to revive an IMF accord signed in
January which collapsed because of Brazil's failure to meet targets.
However, their trip was cancelled after a Brazil congressional commission
delayed its decision on a Dollars 12bn fiscal reform programme essential for
balancing next year's government budget.
The cancellation is the strongest sign yet of the disarray within the
government of President Itamar Franco who took office two months ago as a
result of the impeachment of President Fernando Collor.
Failure to secure an IMF accord could jeopardise Brazil's accord with
creditors over restructuring of its Dollars 44bn commercial debt.
</TEXT>
