<HEADLINE>
FT  02 DEC 92 / London Stock Exchange: Upgrades boost for BTR
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO, CHRISTOPHER PRICE and STEVE THOMPSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INTERNATIONAL con-glomerate BTR moved sharply forward to rate as the day's
best performing FT-SE 100 stock after several brokers upgraded profit
expectations following visits to the company.
The shares jumped 18 1/2 to 517 1/2 p, in brisk trade of 10m after BZW and
James Capel increased current year profits estimates by Pounds 20m to Pounds
1.02bn and by Pounds 15m to Pounds 985m respectively. Mr Mark Cusack at BZW
said of his new forecast, 'efficiency improvements are coming through and
the Hawker Siddeley acquisition is performing ahead of expectations,' while
James Capel reiterated its positive view on 'very early news of signs of a
recovery in the US and Australia'. Further upgradings are expected over the
next few days.
Hong Kong shocks
The fall of 5 per cent in the Hong Kong stock market, as relations between
the British administration and the Chinese government deteriorated, prompted
heavy falls in UK stocks with interests there, notably HSBC, Standard
Chartered and Cable &amp; Wireless.
The most active was HSBC where turnover totalled 12m. Shares in the banking
group tumbled to 493p before picking up to end a net 16 off at 502p. HSBC
shares have been one of the UK market's best performers since the merger
with Midland Bank was effected earlier this year.
Standard Chartered fell 8 to 543p, albeit in much quieter trading, which saw
fewer than 1m shares change hands, with the stock sustained by expectations
that the company will be elevated to the Footsie-100 status for the new
year. Telecoms group Cable &amp; Wireless, which derives well over half of its
income from its stake in Hong Kong Telecom, dropped to 654p before
stabilising to close 6 off at 659p. Turnover was an unremarkable 1.7m
shares.
Asda query
Predictions of an end to Asda's bull run proved correct and the shares fell
back in another day's heavy trading after several brokers turned seller of
the stock. Market attention is now firmly focused on the group's results on
December 18 with talk of a fund-raising excercise doing the rounds. Asda is
said to be in need of a cash injection to boost its capital expenditure
programme which badly lags its rivals. Up to Pounds 100m might need to be
raised, given Asda's debt position. However, a rights issue is not thought
to be a favoured route coming so quickly after last year's and straining
shareholder loyalty. Suggestions in the market say a bond issue might be
preferable. Asda shares retreated 5 1/2 to 52 1/2 p in turnover of 37m, once
again the top traded stock of the day.
Calor move
A couple of exceptionally heavy individual trades in Calor Group shares led
dealers to suspect that SHV, the privately-owned Dutch investment group, had
moved back into the market to increase its stake to just below 50 per cent.
SHV currently has 47.26 per cent of Calor and is allowed to increase its
holding by 2 per cent in the year to next November. SHV's last increase was
announced on November 10. Calor shares held at 224p on turnover of 2.9m.
The oil majors showed signs of struggling as crude oil prices continued to
lose ground, dropping around 40 cents a barrel. BP, helped by a positive
response to the presentation to Scottish institutions, moved up 3 1/2 to
237p. News of the exploration success off the coast of Burma drove Premier
Consolidated up 1 1/4 to 17 3/4 p on heavy turnover of 9.8m shares.
The placing by Warburg Securities of 9.92m Sedgwick shares at a discount of
only 2p to the ruling market price saw Sedgwick close only a penny easier at
144p.
There was little fallout from the demise of Rosehaugh, the market preferring
instead to focus on results from the UK's second biggest property group,
MEPC. Although the figures were in line with expectations, the dire
conditions in the commercial property market meant continuing worries over
the safety of next year's dividend. Net asset values fell from 608p to 465p
and while most analysts are forecasting between 410p and 420p for next year,
at least one leading broker was on 385p and predicting a big dividend cut.
In the meantime, MEPC's hefty discount to the market and high yield meant it
recovered from its initial fall and closed at 337p, off 2.
The launch in the US of Reuters' News2000 system, which enhances Reuters'
news and financial services, was greeted with enthusiasm by the stock market
where Reuters shares jumped 18 to a record 1354p.
The utilities sectors suffered badly during the early part of the session as
institutions continued to switch from the waters and electricity stocks into
the cyclicals. The sectors were additionally unsettled by the Ofwat report
on water standards and delivery costs plus slight disappointment with
results from Norweb, the first of the electricity companies to report
interim figures.
Both sectors rallied strongly, however, closing well above the day's lowest
levels.
Fears for the current year dividend hit Trafalgar House as it reported a
Pounds 30.3m loss and slashed last year's dividend from 18.4p to 6p. The
shares fell 6 to 89p.
Among transport stocks, sellers of Tiphook following last week's strong
performance caused the shares to give up 4 to 275p, in light trading. The
company said yesterday that it had replaced County NatWest and Warburg as
joint brokers with UBS Phillips &amp; Drew.
The expected disposal at APV duly arrived when the company announced the
sale of its ventilation and warm-air hand-dryer business Vent-Axia Group to
Smiths Industries for Pounds 55.8m. Analysts said the move was positive for
both groups and the shares of the former gained 4 1/2 to 107 1/2 p, while
the latter jumped 9 to 335p.
Trading in Rolls-Royce was boosted by a buy recommendation from County
NatWest and turnover rose to 7.8m as the shares firmed a penny to 101p. The
broker said: 'Rolls-Royce offers investors an outstanding opportunity for
long term capital growth.'
Euro Disney continued to crumble as its two principal bears, Goldman Sachs
and Paribas, succeeded in producing even gloomier forecasts. Mr Nigel Reed
at Paribas increased his projected loss for the French theme park by 5 times
to over FFr1bn for the year ended September 1993. Goldman is on FFr750m. The
shares fell 43 to 725p.
Confident expectations ahead of Granada's results today helped the shares
add 6 to 309p. Analysts forecasts of around Pounds 115m are thought likely
to prove around Pounds 7-8m short. Queens Moat continued to attract
attention with 11m shares traded, 3m of which comprised a bed and breakfast
(tax-related) deal. The good two-way business left the shares steady at 45
1/2 p, talk of a deal with other hotel groups refusing to die away.
A stock overhang - said to be around 1.5m shares - continued to hold back
Kwik Save. The shares fell 3 1/2 to 727 1/2 p.
There was general disappointment in the market with interim profits from
Racal Electronics. The latter's shares, which hit an all-time high last
week, dropped 17, or 11 per cent, to 157p, after the figures were released.
Specialists said that although the results were at the very top end of
market estimates, some of the super optimists were slightly disappointed and
that a very substantial bull position in the stock had been unwound
yesterday. Full-year estimates were being reined in from around the Pounds
55m-mark to the Pounds 52m level.
ACT, the computer group, slipped 2 to 141p, following the placing of a block
of 6.5m shares at 137p late on Monday. The placing was executed in a matter
of minutes by Credit Lyonnais Laing, the stockbroker. ACT is using the cash
to help fund its purchase of NMW Computers and repay the latter's bank debt.
