<HEADLINE>
FT  02 DEC 92 / World Stock Markets (Asia Pacific): Hong Kong leads the
losses in a weak region
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Nikkei average fell by 2.1 per cent yesterday as investment trust funds
took profits after the recent rally in share prices, writes Emiko Terazono
in Tokyo.
The 225-issue index fell 370.61 to 17,313.04 after a high of 17,704.01 in
the morning and a low of 17,307.72 just before the close. While prices moved
narrowly in early trading, afternoon selling by dealers and investment
trusts outpaced buying by public funds.
Volume rose marginally to 260m shares from 238m. Declines led advances by
637 to 359 with 133 issues unchanged. The Topix index of all first section
stocks dropped 19.27 to 1,304.08 and in London the ISE/Nikkei 50 index rose
0.54 to 1,054.21.
Traders said that after the 10.5 per cent rise in the Nikkei average over
the past eight trading days, a decline had been expected, but that overall
sentiment remained positive. 'People were starting to become scared of a
possible crash, and we needed a breather,' said Mr Yasuo Ueki at Nikko
Securities. Other traders said some investment trusts placed sell orders to
raise cash for redemptions and cancellations.
High-technology issues, which had risen recently on hopes of a US economic
recovery, were hit by profit-taking. NEC fell Y20 to Y675 and Fujitsu lost
Y17 to Y550. Car stocks were also weaker with Nissan Motor down Y13 to Y557
and Toyota Motor retreating Y10 to Y1,410.
The weakness in Nippon Credit Bank, which lost Y140 to Y4,800, dragged down
other banking stocks. Reports, later denied by Nippon Credit Bank, that the
bank had sold off land taken as collateral for troubled loans to a property
agency, prompted selling by discouraged investors. The Industrial Bank of
Japan fell Y50 to Y2,450 and Mitsubishi Bank lost Y60 to Y2,220.
Dealers took profits on speculative theme stocks. Mitsui Mining and
Smelting, the most active issue of the day, fell Y10 to Y498. Aids-related
issues were also weak with Okamoto down Y10 to Y1,100 and Meiji Milk
Products down Y4 to Y940.
Nippon Housing Loan was one of the few bright spots of the day, rising Y13
to Y288 on short-covering.
In Osaka, the OSE average lost 187.98 to 18,773.07 in volume of 41.7m
shares. The OSE said trading volume for November surged 36.5 per cent to
429.9m shares as an increasing number of life assurers and banks realised
profits on holdings.
Roundup
HONG KONG suffered its biggest one-day fall since August 1991 as
Sino-British tension continued to unnerve investors. The region's other
markets were also negative.
HONG KONG lost another 5 per cent in volatile trading on reports that China
would repudiate contracts signed by the present authorities after 1997. The
Hang Seng index, which fell to an intraday low of 5,400, closed down 308.92
at 5,501.71 in moderate turnover of some HKDollars 3.85bn.
Financial stocks were among the day's biggest losers with HSBC Holdings down
HK3.50 at HKDollars 54.50 and Hang Seng Bank HKDollars 2.50 lower at
HKDollars 50.00.
SEOUL was disappointed that the central bank failed to cut interest rates
and the composite index declined 3.43 to 659.93 in turnover of Won545.8bn.
Kepco, the electricity generator, lost Won700 to Won21,700.
TAIWAN retreated in thin trading as the weighted index lost 28.25 to
3,646.76 in turnover of TDollars 6.34bn. The financial sector, which has
been relatively strong recently, lost nearly 1 per cent.
AUSTRALIA lost ground in late trading as the local currency weakened against
the US dollar. The All Ordinaries index slipped 3.8 to 1,444.3 having been
briefly revived by the publication of better-than-expected economic data.
Turnover rose to ADollars 237.7m from ADollars 188.2m.
NEW ZEALAND fell back as the market consolidated its recent strong gains.
The NZSE-40 Index lost 8 to 1,539.34 in turnover of NZDollars 50m.
SINGAPORE's Straits Times industrial index eased 5.0 to 1,464.07 although
gains were seen among several banking and industrial blue chips. In KUALA
LUMPUR the composite index was also lower, down 4.66 to 637.23.
MANILA rose on bargain-hunting following Monday's holiday and the composite
index finished 2.90 higher at 1,266.48 in turnover of 168.6m pesos.
BANGKOK traded lower with the SET index losing 3.88 to 861.33 in thin
turnover of Bt4bn.
