FT  02 DEC 92 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow rally starts to run out
of steam
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
AFTER registering strong gains in the four previous days, the rally in US
share prices showed signs of running out of steam yesterday, writes Patrick
Harverson in New York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was down 10.80 at 3,295.36,
having spent all but a few minutes of the day in negative territory. The
more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 finished down 0.62 at 430.73, while
the Amex composite ended 2.14 lower at 392.97 and the Nasdaq composite up
1.22 at 653.95, another record close.
Turnover on the NYSE remained heavy at 259m shares, while rises and declines
were neck and neck at 912 and 914, respectively. A combination of weakness
on overseas markets and profit-taking in the wake of recent gains prompted
the early selling.
Positive economic news at home, however, helped prices stage a modest rally
later, although it proved short-lived and selling again took hold in
mid-afternoon. A 0.4 per cent rise in the October index of leading economic
indicators, and the National Association of Purchasing Management's November
index, which climbed from 50.6 in October to 55.0, was the latest more proof
that the economy is recovering.
Among individual stocks, Digital Equipment, which enjoyed big gains during
Monday's sector-wide rally, dropped Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars 32 7/8 in
turnover of 2.3m shares amid rumours of a development problem with the
company's Alpha technology which is at the heart of a future product
strategy. Digital denied that it was experiencing any such problems with
Alpha.
Unisys climbed Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 9 3/4 in turnover of 3.1m shares
after broking house Josephthal Lyon &amp; Ross upgraded the stock from a 'hold'
to a 'buy'. Profit-taking left IBM Dollars  1/2 lower at Dollars 67 3/4 ,
and Hewlett-Packard down Dollars 2 3/8 at Dollars 64 1/8 .
Chemical stocks were in demand, with Du Pont rising Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars
49 1/4 , Dow Chemical putting on Dollars 1 5/8 at Dollars 54 7/8 . Monsanto,
which rose early on, ended unchanged at Dollars 56 1/8 .
LSI Logic rose Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 10 in busy trading after the company
cancelled the three-day shutdown that it had planned for later this month
and said it expected to achieve 'solid profitability' in the fourth quarter.
Baker Hughes dropped Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars 18 3/8 in turnover of 2.1m
shares after warning that first-quarter net income would come in below
market forecasts of 19 cents a share. The group did say, however, that
profits in the remaining three quarters would be better than in the same
period of 1992.
Canada
TORONTO stocks finished lower after a heavy trading session with most
indices losing ground.
The TSE 300 slipped 9.2 to 3273.7 on 36m shares valued at CDollars 352.9m.
